\section{Introduction}
\label{intro}

The Solenoid Tracker At RHIC (STAR)~\cite{star_det} is one of the major high energy nuclear physics experiments in Relativistic Heavy Ion Collider (RHIC) at Brookhaven National Laboratory. 
After 15 years of operation, the STAR experiment provided us lots of important physics results in understanding the properties of Quantum Chromodynamics (QCD). 
Especially the evidence of the existence of Quark-Gluon Plasma opened a new window to get a deeper insight into QCD~\cite{dis_qgp}. 

Heavy quark-antiquark states are perfect probes to study the properties of the QCD matter.
For instance, quarkonium suppression in the medium due to the color-screening of the surrounding partons can provide information about the partonic nature of the QGP and its temperature~\cite{jpsi_supp, pot_mod}. 
To reconstruct the quarkonium states via the leptonic decay, the dimuon channel suffers less combinatoric background and Bremsstrahlung radiation compared to the dielectron channel.

A new subdetector in STAR, Muon Telescope Detector (MTD), dedicated to measuring muons was proposed in 2009 and was installed from 2012 to 2014~\cite{mtd, mtd_2}.

In this paper, we present the muon identification performance of this new detector. 

This paper is arranged as follows. 
In Section 2, a brief description of the STAR detector is presented. 
The dateset and event selection are shown in Section 3.
In Section 4, three methods used to identify muon candidates are described. 
In Section 5, we present the efficinecy as well as the resulting signal significance for $J/\psi$ from these three methods. 
Finally, a summary is given in Section 6. 

\section{The STAR detector}
\label{star}
The STAR detector is a general purpose particle detector focused on high energy nuclear physics. 

The main subsystems relevant to this analysis include the Time Projection Camber (TPC), the Magnet System and the MTD. 
The TPC is the major tracking detector for charged particles in STAR and measures the ionization energy loss (dE/dx) which plays an important role in particle identification~\cite{tpc}. 
It covers full azimuthal angle ($0 < \phi < 2 \pi$) and large pseudorapidity range ($|\eta| < 1$). 


The Magnet System generates 0.5 Tesla of magnetic field to bend the charged particles. 
There are 30 flux-return bars, known as "backlegs", outside the coil to provide the return flux path for the magnet field~\cite{magnet}. 
These backlegs play an essential role in enhancing the muon purity by absorbing the background hadrons from collisions.


The MTD is a fast detector based on the Multi-gap Resistive Plate Chamber technology to record signals, also referred to as "hits", generated by charged particles traversing it. 
It covers about 45\% in azimuth within $|\eta| <$ 0.5.


Out of the full MTD system, 10\%, 63\% and 100\% was installed in 2012, 2013, and 2014, respectively.
The timing and spatial resolution of the MTD obtained from cosmic ray data are $\sim$100 ps and $\sim$1-2 cm, respectively~\cite{mtd_3}.  



\subsection{Data and Monte Carlo}
Data for this study were collected by the STAR detector during the RHIC proton-proton run at center-of-mass energy of 500 GeV in 2013. 
Events in the data sample were selected using the MTD triggers. After the basic track selection described in the next section, more than 1500 $J/\psi \to\mu^+\mu^-$ candidates are used in this study. 

In order to have pure and larger statistics muon sample, the Monte Carlo of the $J/\psi \to \mu^+ \mu^- $ signal was used in this study.  
The sample was generated by a single-particle generator with flat distributions in $J/\psi$ transverse momentum ($p_T$), $\phi$ and $\eta$. These simulated signals were then passed through the full GEANT3 simulation of the STAR detector, and ``embedded'' into real events followed by the standard reconstruction procedure as used for real data.
For comparison, the kinematic distributions of the embedded $J/\psi$ and $\mu^{\pm}$ were weighted by the $p_T$ spectrum of $J/\psi$ in pp collisions at 500 GeV determined via interpolation through a global fit of differential $J/\psi$ cross section from world-wide measurements~\cite{jpsi_pt}.








\subsection{Track selection}
Tracks selected for the muon identification study should meet the following requirements: 
$p_T$ is greater than 1 GeV/c; 

the distance of closest approach to the collision vertex should be less than 3 cm to suppress secondary decays; 
number of TPC clusters used in reconstruction should be greater than 15 (the maximum possible is 45) to have good momentum resolution; 
number of TPC clusters used for the dE/dx measurement is greater than 10 to ensure good dE/dx resolution;
the ratio of the number of TPC clusters over the number of possible clusters is not less than 0.52 in order to reject split tracks. 

For muon candidates, tracks are also required to match to the MTD hits that fire the triggers. 

























Figure~\ref{fig:dimuon_mass} shows the dimuon mass spectrum with the selection criteria described above on both muons and it is clear to see the $J/\psi$ signal around 3.1 $GeV/c^2$. However, the light mesons, like $\omega$, $\phi$ and $\eta$ particles, are not obvious due to the huge background. 


