\section{Muon identification}
\label{muid}


To distinguish muon candidates from the hadron background in the MTD, there are four variables, $\Delta$ToF, $\Delta y\times q$, $\Delta z$ and $n\sigma_{\pi}$ used in this study.  
$\Delta$ToF is the difference between the calculated time-of-light value from track extrapolation with a muon particle hypothesis and the measured one from the MTD detector. 
$\Delta y$ and $\Delta z$ are the position differences between the MTD hit position and extrapolated track position on the MTD. 


$\Delta y$ is multiplied by charge ($\Delta y\times q$) to eliminate the charge dependence. 
$n\sigma_{\pi}$ is the normalized $dE/dx$ quantity to the theoretical value of pions, defined as
